Notebook[{
Cell["Metric Algebra Tutorial", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"3f98edda-a8d2-4aed-b47d-a456d110e724"],

Cell["\<\
The metric algebra layer organises numerical invariants of the shortest-path \
metric: the metric interval, geodesic multiplicities, the \
geodesic-multiplicity matrix, and median vertices. These are the \
synthetic-to-analytic-to-algebraic bridge: distances on a graph become \
matrices that the higher synthetic / Tarski layers query through one-line \
conditions on the pair (A, D).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0c17c72f-2a32-416d-84c2-3142ec7d7734"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"20eb803b-5d97-4d62-9489-a4ee4ec619a8"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"9455711b-5326-4eb3-9269-136efa32bfe4"],

Cell["The metric interval", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"63bbca3d-0b6d-47c4-b8ab-9a093455f637"],

Cell["\<\
The metric interval I(u, v) = { w : d(u, w) + d(w, v) == d(u, v) } is the \
union of all geodesics from u to v -- the master operation of the metric \
algebra layer.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5c21722e-36d4-4221-81e3-21a4784b84f5"],

Cell["MetricInterval[GridGraph[{3, 3}], 1, 9]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"de9482de-2561-4379-8f4d-de7a73681f1e"],

Cell["\<\
The interval contains every vertex on every shortest 1-9 path. On a tree the \
interval is exactly the unique geodesic vertex set; on a grid it is much \
wider.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a13420bc-71f5-4905-a4a4-ebbaeca5bb84"],

Cell["Geodesic multiplicities", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"415e9b19-4847-4f03-b6a6-55ca53137e91"],

Cell["\<\
GeodesicMultiplicity[g, u, v] returns the number of distinct geodesics from u \
to v. Computed in polynomial time as (A^d)[u, v] where A is the adjacency \
matrix and d = d(u, v).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"65319f47-787d-490e-8908-1dd0d6436229"],

Cell["GeodesicMultiplicity[GridGraph[{3, 3}], 1, 9]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"609c9e54-f6d7-4202-be70-2a690e81333e"],

Cell["GeodesicMultiplicity[CycleGraph[6], 1, 4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"4522c634-d030-44a3-a284-ac6c9964dcf1"],

Cell["\<\
Six geodesics on the grid (the lattice paths from one corner to the other) \
and two on the cycle (one for each side).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0fa7db7c-b567-407c-ad77-bd8eebbfe93c"],

Cell["The geodesic-multiplicity matrix", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"73b111d8-2113-47da-b481-fdf791ae6e49"],

Cell["\<\
GeodesicMultiplicityMatrix[g] returns {D, M} where D is the n x n distance \
matrix and M is the geodesic-count matrix.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4d7df7bb-aea6-4ca8-912a-e531357905cf"],

Cell["\<\
{distMat, mulMat} = GeodesicMultiplicityMatrix[GridGraph[{3, 3}]]; \
MatrixForm[mulMat]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"d857dfca-5b88-48d6-a7bb-064285b12352"],

Cell["\<\
Reading off the global geodesic counts: each entry of mulMat counts the \
geodesics between the corresponding vertex pair.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a797025a-30d9-45b3-bde5-f71f38e7e1f5"],

Cell["Median vertices", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8dafe2ff-c6a4-482f-a95b-2928a2dc813e"],

Cell["\<\
MedianVertices[g, vs] returns the vertices minimising the sum of graph \
distances to the given vertex list. For a triple {a, b, c} this is the metric \
median(s); a graph is a median graph iff every triple has a unique median.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"71e9d8fc-06f2-4a55-abaa-bba30da6dd50"],

Cell["MedianVertices[HypercubeGraph[3], {1, 4, 6}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"b544f9cc-c455-481d-9ab2-5cd75e98cc3a"],

Cell["\<\
Hypercubes are median graphs (the median is unique). The 6-cycle is not:\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"a48460cb-b255-4294-b12e-5d2c46650d57"],

Cell["MedianVertices[CycleGraph[6], {1, 3, 5}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"b2774105-6750-4ac7-b501-b945fa9a3414"],

Cell["Geodesic convex hulls", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"9390e9df-3832-4191-95f9-b9e6342671e6"],

Cell["\<\
FindGeodesicConvexHull[g, vs] is the smallest geodesically convex superset of \
vs -- the closure of vs under FindSegment. GeodesicallyConvexQ tests whether \
a vertex set is already closed.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d30946a0-f622-4e2b-ad28-1a4ce38cace9"],

Cell["FindGeodesicConvexHull[GridGraph[{4, 4}], {1, 4, 16}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"090d6022-df2b-4927-8110-75f5df92b993"],

Cell["GeodesicallyConvexQ[GridGraph[{4, 4}], {1, 2, 3, 4}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"e089ccfa-4e1f-48d8-9bbb-bf3130f64bee"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"eb2c280f-347c-487e-aba3-8e842146c4e5"],

Cell["MetricAlgebraGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"df80f0a6-9d69-4fbf-b132-31027461b397"],

Cell["TropicalConvexityGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"2bcf6edf-c159-4845-a2e6-1aa39d8a63d9"],

Cell["EuclideanGeometryGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dabeb72d-fb94-4d21-a714-532c802c7af9"],

Cell["TarskiGeometryGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5e351473-c4cc-4dd9-8a68-d2fe3ad1a590"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"748832f6-0afa-4dae-9ed4-7eec525109b2"],

Cell["\<\
Mulder, The Interval Function of a Graph, Mathematical Centre Tracts 132, \
Amsterdam 1980.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ad7f597d-9231-427b-90e8-54d2982073de"],

Cell["\<\
Bandelt and Mulder, Distance-Hereditary Graphs, J. Combin. Theory Ser. B 41, \
182-208, 1986.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f4edbdbc-4f80-4e42-b820-47e9ee8cf030"],

Cell["\<\
Linial, Geodesic Geometry on Graphs, \
https://www.cs.huji.ac.il/~nati/PAPERS/ge_ge_gr.pdf\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"39497534-bffe-4c85-adc2-a14e84a0c96c"]
},
